tines on military bases.\n\nShe agreed to keep a daily journal of her time in quarantine. Here is some of her diary, edited for length and clarity.\n\nDay 1\n\nThe U.S. embassy staff checked my body temperature, and gave me a green wristband. The color represented which flight I would take. One other U.S. flight was going out, too, and people were given yellow wristbands for that.\n\nDay 2\n\nWhen we got off the airplane at a military base in San Diego, workers from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention stood by in navy blue jackets with huge C.D.C. logos.\n\nEverything looked like the movie \"Contagion.\"\n\nDay 5\n\nI made myself a cup of coffee. Looking out of the window from my room, it's a beautiful dawn view. I cannot even grasp where I am and what I am going through. The jet lag hit me badly.\n\nI checked my phone. One message dragged me back to the reality in Wuhan. One of my friends texted to say that his grandma and auntie both passed away from the coronavirus. His dad was still in the hospital.\n\nAll of it took me back to everything I had seen in Wuhan.\n\nDay 5\n\nRight before I left Wuhan, I went to my grandparents' home with my mom to say goodbye. That was the first time I saw my grandpa cry. I could not hug or even touch them.\n\nMy grandma handed me a bag with a red envelope and a letter my grandpa had written to me. I held my tears and said goodbye.\n\nDay 6\n\nBack on the base, two people in quarantine have tested positive for the coronavirus. People are starting to question the C.D.C. staff.\n\nI have so many questions in my mind, too. But I trust the staff who have supported us since this started and are working 14 hours a day.\n\n\"We're the lucky ones,\" I keep saying to people in here. Obviously, not everybody thinks like me. They wrote a petition asking for coronavirus tests for everyone.\n\nDay 6\n\nWe went to a town hall of the people in quarantine. A C.D.C. officer told us that someone with coronavirus was accidentally brought back to the base briefly because of a testing mistake.\n\nPeople were very angry. They were anxious and wanted to know the names of people who are ill. For privacy reasons, the C.D.C. officer didn't tell us. I understand people's concerns, but I think it's overreacting and pointless.\n\nDay 8\n\nI am not the kind of person who likes to celebrate these sorts of special days. I'm single now, so I have no feeling about Valentine's Day. (Keep calm and carry on.)\n\nBut I wanted to do something to break up this long and boring quarantine. So I ordered Godiva chocolate and gift cards online. I wanted to share them with my dear \"neighbors\" here in quarantine, two young professional women.\n\nI knocked on my neighbors' doors and -- keeping the 6-foot distance we've been asked to keep -- passed the bags to them.\n\nDay 8\n\nI went to the regular temperature check in the morning. I gave the C.D.C. staff a Valentine's Day note.\n\nDay 8\n\nAfter about 10 days in quarantine, I actually see myself as happier than before. I've learned to check the phone less and focus on myself.\n\nI've read books that I hadn't finished for years. I worked a puzzle in my room alone for six hours.\n\nDay 8\n\nWhat am I missing the most? The dish my mom and grandma cooked for me when I was in Wuhan.\n\nIn here, I spend two or three hours a day contacting my family and friends in Wuhan. I have made new friends here and we talk during breakfast. But mostly I don't go outside or spend time with other people.\n\nDay 9\n\nThe mood has changed a lot here, day by day. The first couple of days, I was feeling safe and finally could sleep better. After the two confirmed cases came out, I felt scared and panicky a little while.\n\nDay 9\n\nI'm not a doctor or a professional, but I've been through this. On a physical level, protection is a must. Wear face masks and wash your hands properly and use sanitizer frequently. But on a mental level, do not overreact!\n\nDay 9\n\nWe should feel sorry for the people who died because of it. Be respectful to people who are working on it and trying to fix the problem. We should appreciate that we're the lucky ones.\n\nDon't put your hate and anxiety on others. It doesn't solve anything.\n\nDay 14\n\nThe whole morning was busy, with packing and checking out from the inn on the military base.\n\nWe all got a yellow A4-size envelope with a letter stating that we are not a coronavirus risk.\n\nDay 14\n\nI am waiting for a flight in San Diego's airport. It feels so unreal after these days: Everything is normal. No one is wearing face masks. People are sitting around me eating lunch and discussing their lives.\n\nI need some time to adjust my mind. It has been a long wait and a journey to get back home.", "source": {"uri": "nytimes.com", "dataType": "news", "title": "The New York Times"}, "authors": [], "concepts": [{"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wristband", "type": "wiki", "score": 5, "label": {"eng": "Wristband"}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coronavirus", "type": "wiki", "score": 5, "label": {"eng": "Coronavirus"}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quarantine", "type": "wiki", "score": 5, "label": {"eng": "Quarantine"}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wuhan", "type": "loc", "score": 5, "label": {"eng": "Wuhan"}, "location": {"type": "place", "label": {"eng": "Wuhan"}, "country": {"type": "country", "label": {"eng": "China"}}}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zong_4G", "type": "org", "score": 4, "label": {"eng": "Zong 4G"}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Military_base", "type": "wiki", "score": 4, "label": {"eng": "Military base"}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federal_government_of_the_United_States", "type": "loc", "score": 4, "label": {"eng": "Federal government of the United States"}, "location": null}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Startup_company", "type": "wiki", "score": 4, "label": {"eng": "Startup company"}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epidemic", "type": "w